### Extending Interfaces

Interfaces can extend one or more other interfaces, inheriting their properties.

### Single Extension

```typescript
interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

interface Employee extends Person {
  employeeId: number;
  department: string;
}

const employee: Employee = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 30,
  employeeId: 123,
  department: "Engineering"
};
```

### Multiple Extension

```typescript
interface Named {
  name: string;
}

interface Aged {
  age: number;
}

interface Contact {
  email: string;
}

interface Person extends Named, Aged, Contact {
  isActive: boolean;
}

// Person has: name, age, email, isActive
```

### Overriding Properties

You can override inherited property types:

```typescript
interface Base {
  id: string;
}

interface Derived extends Base {
  id: number; // OK, narrows or widens
}
```

### Extending from Multiple Sources

```typescript
interface Shape {
  color: string;
}

interface Dimensions {
  width: number;
  height: number;
}

interface Rectangle extends Shape, Dimensions {
  borderRadius?: number;
}

const rect: Rectangle = {
  color: "red",
  width: 100,
  height: 50
};
```

### Interface vs Type Extension

| Feature | Interface extends | Type intersection |
|---------|------------------|-------------------|
| Syntax | `extends` | `&` |
| Conflicts | Override (with check) | Never (creates never) |
| Reopening | Yes (declaration merging) | No |

> **Key Point:** Interface extension creates a single flat type, not an intersection.

codeExample:
interface Timestamp {
  createdAt: Date;
  updatedAt: Date;
}

interface SoftDelete {
  deletedAt?: Date;
  isDeleted: boolean;
}

// Multiple extension
interface DatabaseRecord extends Timestamp, SoftDelete {
  id: number;
  data: unknown;
}

const record: DatabaseRecord = {
  id: 1,
  data: { key: "value" },
  createdAt: new Date(),
  updatedAt: new Date(),
  isDeleted: false
};
